label.value: Syncope with High Risk Cardiac Characteristics

definition.value: A sudden loss of consciousness with loss of postural tone not related to anesthesia with high risk characteristics. High risk characteristics include non-ischemic dilated cardiomyopathy, or ischemic heart disease with significant ventricular dysfunction, hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, Brugada Syndrome, or Long QT Syndrome. (ACC)
An injury sustained to a neonate during the birthing process.

label.value: European Quality of Life Five Dimension Five Level Scale Questionnaire

definition.value: A standardized rating scale which is used as a measure of health outcome. This instrument is a descriptive system consisting of 5 dimensions: mobility, self-care, usual activity, pain/discomfort, and anxiety/depression. Each dimension has 5 levels ranging from no problem to extreme problem or incapable, which are assessed by the patient.

label.value: Short Form 36 Health Survey Standard, US Version 2.0 Questionnaire

definition.value: A standardized, multipurpose, general health survey developed by John E. Ware and copyrighted by Quality Metric Inc. and the Medical Outcomes Trust in 1996 and 2000 which is used to assess the patient's functional health and overall well-being. This second version contains 36 questions that refer to the patient's symptoms or status within the past four weeks and can be completed by the patient. For each question the patient must choose from five different responses.
A standardized rating scale used to assess an individual's general level of daytime sleepiness.
A seven item validated, self-reported questionnaire for screening, and assessing the severity of generalized anxiety disorder in clinical practice and research settings.

label.value: Hospital Anxiety and Depression Scale Questionnaire

definition.value: A standardized survey developed and copyrighted by A. S. Zigmond and R. P. Snaith in 1983, 1992, 1994 and published in the Acta Psychiatrica Scandinavica journal (A.S. Zigmond and R.P. Snaith. The Hospital Anxiety and Depression Scale. Acta psychiart. scand. 1983, 67:361-370) which is used to detect depression and anxiety in individuals in a hospital or medical outpatient clinic. This instrument is a self-administered questionnaire consisting of 14 items that assess how the individual has felt over the past week. Each item as 4 response options that are associated with a score of 0 to 3.

A 9-item scale using each of the 9 DSM-IV criteria with self-reported frequency of "0" (not at all) to "3" (nearly every day). One of the most widely used instruments to assess depression, PHQ-9 scores of 5, 10, 15, and 20 represent mild, moderate, moderately severe, and severe depression, respectively.
A self-rated questionnaire which assesses sleep quality and disturbances over a one month time interval.
A 9 question subset of the Treatment Satisfaction Questionnaire for Medication that omits the five items of the side effects domain.
The determination of the amount of ghrelin present in a sample.

label.value: Have Feeling of Fullness or Heaviness in Stomach Area

definition.value: A question about whether an individual has or had a feeling of fullness or heaviness in the area of the stomach.

A complication occurring during hemodialysis that is thought to be due to a rapid decrease in blood urea nitrogen, and is characterized by an increase in intracranial pressure resulting in nausea, headache, vomiting, restlessness, and/or a decreased level of consciousness.
A technique that monitors blood oxygen level dependent (BOLD) signals to map distant brain regions that work together while performing a task.
An extension of conventional diffusion tension imaging, which estimates the kurtosis of the water diffusion probability distribution function. This technique is most commonly used to study the brain.
A collection of blood between the dura mater and the brain.
The use of electrodes placed directly on the exposed brain surface to record the electrical activity of the cerebral cortex.
A condition characterized by recurrent, self-limiting episodes of vomiting associated with intense nausea, pallor, and lethargy. It is commonly a migraine precursor.
